{
  "name": "Synthesise Completed Specs",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "description": "Reviews all specs with 100% complete tasks, synthesises their requirements/bugfix and design files into repo-level steering documents (requirements.md and architecture.md), then deletes the completed specs. Establishes the convention that future specs extend or alter these repo-level documents.",
  "when": {
    "type": "userTriggered"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "The user wants to synthesise all completed specs into repo-level steering documents. Follow this workflow exactly:\n\n## Step 1: Discover All Specs\n\n1. List all directories under `.kiro/specs/`.\n2. If there are NO spec directories, tell the user there are no specs to synthesise and stop.\n3. For each spec directory, read the `tasks.md` file.\n\n## Step 2: Identify Completed Specs\n\n1. A spec is 100% complete when ALL tasks in its `tasks.md` are checked (marked `[x]`).\n2. If a task line contains `[ ]` (unchecked), the spec is NOT complete.\n3. Build a list of completed specs and a list of incomplete specs.\n4. Report to the user: \"Found X completed specs and Y incomplete specs.\"\n5. List the completed specs by name.\n6. If there are NO completed specs, tell the user and stop.\n7. Ask the user: \"Shall I proceed with synthesising these completed specs?\" Wait for confirmation before continuing.\n\n## Step 3: Read All Completed Spec Files\n\nFor each completed spec, read:\n- `requirements.md` (if it exists — used for feature/task specs)\n- `bugfix.md` (if it exists — used for bug specs)\n- `design.md` (if it exists)\n- `tasks.md` (for reference only — you will not synthesise tasks)\n\nCollect all the content. Understand the full picture of what was built and why.\n\n## Step 4: Check for Existing Repo-Level Documents\n\n1. Check whether `.kiro/steering/requirements.md` already exists.\n2. Check whether `.kiro/steering/architecture.md` already exists.\n3. If either exists, read its current content — you will be EXTENDING it, not replacing it.\n\n## Step 5: Synthesise Requirements\n\nCreate or update `.kiro/steering/requirements.md` with the following structure:\n\n- Add YAML frontmatter: `inclusion: manual` (this is a reference document, not always-on guidance).\n- The file should be titled \"# Repository Requirements & Correctness Properties\".\n- Synthesise ALL requirements from completed specs' `requirements.md` files into a unified set of correctness properties.\n- Synthesise ALL bug specifications from completed specs' `bugfix.md` files into correctness properties (convert the \"Expected Behavior\" and \"Unchanged Behavior\" sections into SHALL/SHALL NOT requirements).\n- Group requirements by domain or feature area, not by original spec.\n- Remove duplicates — if two specs defined the same requirement, include it once.\n- Use EARS notation consistently: WHEN [condition] THE SYSTEM SHALL [behavior].\n- Include regression prevention properties from bugfix specs.\n- If the file already existed, merge new requirements into the existing structure. Do not lose existing content.\n\n## Step 6: Synthesise Architecture\n\nCreate or update `.kiro/steering/architecture.md` with the following structure:\n\n- Add YAML frontmatter: `inclusion: manual` (this is a reference document, not always-on guidance).\n- The file should be titled \"# Repository Architecture\".\n- Synthesise ALL design decisions from completed specs' `design.md` files into a unified architecture document.\n- Cover: system components, data flow, key design decisions and their rationale, technology choices, integration points.\n- Group by architectural concern (e.g. data layer, API layer, infrastructure) not by original spec.\n- Remove duplicates and resolve contradictions (if two specs made conflicting design decisions, use the most recent one and note the evolution).\n- If the file already existed, merge new architectural decisions into the existing structure. Do not lose existing content.\n\n## Step 7: Present Results for Review\n\n1. Show the user the synthesised `requirements.md` content.\n2. Show the user the synthesised `architecture.md` content.\n3. Ask: \"Here are the synthesised documents. Would you like to refine anything before I delete the completed specs?\"\n4. Wait for explicit confirmation. Iterate if the user requests changes.\n\n## Step 8: Delete Completed Specs\n\nOnce the user confirms:\n\n1. For each completed spec, delete the entire spec directory under `.kiro/specs/` (all files within it).\n2. Report which spec directories were deleted.\n3. Do NOT delete incomplete specs.\n\n## Step 9: Summary\n\nTell the user:\n- How many specs were synthesised and deleted.\n- Where the synthesised documents live (`.kiro/steering/requirements.md` and `.kiro/steering/architecture.md`).\n- Remind them of the new convention:\n  - Future specs should define their requirements as extensions to or alterations of `.kiro/steering/requirements.md`.\n  - Future designs should be specific implementation designs for the spec, and/or adjustments or extensions to `.kiro/steering/architecture.md`.\n  - When a future spec is completed and this hook is run again, its requirements and design will be merged into the repo-level documents.\n\n## Rules\n\n1. NEVER delete a spec that has incomplete tasks.\n2. NEVER replace existing content in the repo-level documents — always merge and extend.\n3. NEVER proceed with deletion without explicit user confirmation.\n4. NEVER synthesise tasks.md — only requirements/bugfix and design files are synthesised.\n5. Use tasks.md only as reference to understand implementation context.\n6. Keep the synthesised documents concise and well-structured — these are living reference documents, not archives.\n7. If a completed spec has neither requirements.md nor bugfix.md, note this to the user but still process its design.md if present.\n8. If a completed spec has no design.md, note this to the user but still process its requirements/bugfix files if present."
  }
}
